  "prompt": "The resultant of two forces has magnitude 20N. One of the forces has magnitude 20\u221a3N making an angle of 30\u00b0 with the resultant? What is the magnitude of the other force?",
  "response": "To solve this problem, we can use vector addition and trigonometry. Let's denote the two forces as \\(\\vec{F_1}\\) and \\(\\vec{F_2}\\), where \\(|\\vec{F_1}| = 20\\sqrt{3}\\) N, the resultant \\(\\vec{R}\\) has a magnitude of 20 N, and the angle between \\(\\vec{F_1}\\) and \\(\\vec{R}\\) is 30\u00b0.\n\nWe need to find the magnitude of the second force \\(|\\vec{F_2}|\\).\n\nSince these are vectors, we can use the law of cosines in vector form:\n\n\\[\n|\\vec{R}|^2 = |\\vec{F_1}|^2 + |\\vec{F_2}|^2 + 2|\\vec{F_1}||\\vec{F_2}|\\cos(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(|\\vec{R}| = 20\\) N, \\(|\\vec{F_1}| = 20\\sqrt{3}\\) N, and \\(\\theta = 30\u00b0\\).\n\nPlugging in the known values:\n\n\\[\n20^2 = (20\\sqrt{3})^2 + |\\vec{F_2}|^2 + 2(20\\sqrt{3})|\\vec{F_2}|\\cos(30\u00b0)\n\\]\n\n\\[\n400 = 1200 + |\\vec{F_2}|^2 + 40\\sqrt{3}|\\vec{F_2}|\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right)\n\\]\n\nSimplifying further:\n\n\\[\n400 = 1200 + |\\vec{F_2}|^2 + 60|\\vec{F_2}|\n\\]\n\nRearrange the terms:\n\n\\[\n|\\vec{F_2}|^2 + 60|\\vec{F_2}| + 800 = 0\n\\]\n\nThis quadratic equation can be solved using the quadratic formula:\n\n\\[\n|\\vec{F_2}| = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(a = 1\\), \\(b = 60\\), and \\(c = 800\\).\n\nThe discriminant \\(b^2 - 4ac\\) is:\n\n\\[\n60^2 - 4 \\times 1 \\times 800 = 3600 - 3200 = 400\n\\]\n\nTaking the square root of the discriminant gives us:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt{400} = 20\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the solutions are:\n\n\\[\n|\\vec{F_2}| = \\frac{-60 \\pm 20}{2}\n\\]\n\nThis gives us two potential solutions:\n\n1. \\(|\\vec{F_2}| = \\frac{-60 + 20}{2} = -20\\) (which is not feasible for a magnitude)\n2. \\(|\\vec{F_2}| = \\frac{-60 - 20}{2} = -40\\) (negative sign indicates direction, but the magnitude is 40)\n\nThe feasible magnitude for \\(|\\vec{F_2}|\\) is 40 N.",
